@node introduction "I forget alot of stuff..."
@{jcenter}@{b}Introduction@{ub}
@{jleft}
	I had written this so I could remember the various things I need to do. Having
a rabid case of ADHD (how many geeks don't?), and a busy schedule, several "oh, shit!"
moments happened late at night when I'm trying to sleep. So now, I have ToDoman, which
helps me organize what I need to do.
	One of the nicer features in this is the ability to link one to-do item to a
completely different list, so double-clicking on it will give a more detailed view of
what needs to be done. This is @{b}really@{ub} handy when it comes to programming. I tend
to forget alot of specifics when I wander off to do something else, so I have this set
up to remind me of various things I need to be working on when I return (usually after
waiting for my 68060 to compile something).
	Also, while I'm programming, I tend to be in a shell alot, and banging away at
the keyboard while my mouse starts feeling lonely and neglected. So instead of
pampering the mouse, I wrote a CLI based todo viewer, handy when I use a full-screen
shell program. I suppose I could have it redirect to the speak: device, but that might
get annoying...
	The shell version has a "scriptlist" option, inspired from the "lformat" option
of the list command. I use the lformat option of list to a degree that should be 
banned in 49 states, so I thought something similar would be handy for to-do.
(Especially if the list is a series of scripts you need to run, but thats a bit too
geeky. Possible, but geeky...)
	Anyway, hopefully its useful to others, and won't cause a computer to melt/
explode/etc... Enjoy!

@endnode

@node installation "How to install it"
@{jcenter}@{b}Usage@{ub}
@{u}Installation@{uu}
@{jleft}
	To install it, drag the executable to wherever you think it should go. (I put
mine in sys:tools/, but you could stick it in sys:trashcan if that works better for
you ;)
	The file @{b}todo@{ub} (without the dash) is a CLI-only program, and should
go in you path somewhere if you plan on using it (I put it in C:).
@{jcenter}@{u}DefIcons@{uu}
@{jleft}
	If you use deficons, you might be interested in the def_todo.info files in
the icons directory (os 3.9 and powericons versions). To work with deficons, just
set up a new sub-category of text file called todo, and match @{b}$VER: ToDoman .1Ô@{ub}
at offset 0. Then copy def_todo.info to envarc:sys (and env:sys, if you don't want
to reboot to test it out).
@endnode

@node settings "How to configure it"
@{jcenter}@{b}Settings@{ub}
@{jleft}
	This part is rather sparse. Currently, you can only change the display format
of the due date. The Acii, html, and csv tabs allow you to change the format for 
exporting those types of files.

@endnode

@node usage "How to use it"
@{jcenter}@{b}Usage@{ub}
@{jcenter}@{u}The main window@{uu}
@{jleft}
	Double clicking it will open the window, and you are presented with a blank
list, with gadgets all over. Anyway, the 2 ghosted arrows on the top-left are history
navigation buttons. As you load new lists, you can return to the previous ones with
those, but it only remembers 10 filenames. Next to that is a string gadget, where you
can view/type a filename for ToDo to load. If you prefer ASL requesters, thats what the
button next to it does. The floppy disk saves the current list. As of this writing, I
was too lazy to ghost it when there isn't a list loaded, so pressing it now will cause
an error requester. (Fixing that is actually an item on one of my lists ;)
	Below that are 2 tabs, called "list" and "Notes". Guess what those are for? ;)
Anyway, the items will appear in "list", with the appropriate information in the right
column. Unless theres another bug I have to squash.. Clicking the "Notes" tab will
reveal a ghosted texteditor, which will remain ghosted until you click on a to-do item.
The big "Save Note" button does just that whenever you're done editing a note. This
feature was added mostly to accompany the same under PalmOS's to-do list, so when I get
around to writing an import script for that, I can still use it.
	Below the notes and list tabs are 2 rows of gadgetry, for when you edit the list.
The only one that shouldn't be ghosted is the "Add" button. Pressing that will, of course,
add a new item. Literally. "New Item" will pop up in the list. Because its not done, it
will be bold faced (completed items are italicized), and nothing appears under the "Done?"
column. "--" should appear under the "Due Date" column, because you haven't selected one
yet. Typing in the string gadget with "New Item" in it will change "New Item" to something
 like "Wash My Socks", or "Feed the dog", or "Give Nate Webb $US10,000,000", or whatever
(only after hitting enter, though). If you have another list to link this to, the string
gadget below that is where the path/filename goes. Or just use the ASL button if you
prefer. The check box completes the item, putting a "*" in the done column, and italicizing
everything. If you go to the notes tab now, it won't be ghosted, and you can enter any
notes you think are useful.
@{jcenter}@{u}Menus@{uu}
@{jleft}
	Theres also some menus. The usual "New", "Load List", "Save List", "Save as", 
"Quit", and "About" (Both ToDo and MUI) are all under project, and behave like 99% of
Amiga proggys menus of those names do. The About ToDo menu also has an AREXX  tab,
detailing the other AREXX commands I've added.
	Also, if you want to import a PalmOS tododb.pdb file, the "Load List" will 
auto-detect it. Currently, you can't export back to PalmOS, but I'm working on that.
	The entries menu has "add", "remove", and "purge completed", which do pretty
much what their name implies. I didn't put a "purge completed" button on the main
window, because my clumsy hand will probably click it and wipe out half my weeks
schedule. Not that I need help finding an excuse for that...
	The last menu is the "Export" menu, so you can save the list in a format that
won't require an emulator on somebody else's system. CSV, Ascii, and HTML are supported.
The Palm entry isn't supported yet, though I will add that when time allows.

@{b}Project@{ub}
	@{u}New@{uu}		- Clear current list and start a new one.
	@{u}Load List@{uu}	- Load a list (ASL req.)
	@{u}Save List@{uu}	- Save current list (overwrites original)
	@{u}Save As...@{uu}	- Save current list with new name (ASL req.)
	--
	@{u}About To-Do@{uu}	- Obligitory brag window
	@{u}About MUI@{uu}	- About MUI, as requested in dev. docs.
	--
	@{u}Quit@{uu}		- Quit to-do
@{b}Entries@{ub}
	@{u}Add@{uu}		- Create new entry (Same as button)
	@{u}Remove@{uu}		- Delete selected entry (Same as button)
	@{u}Purge@{uu}		- Delete all completed entries.
@{b}Export@{ub}
	@{u}ASCII@{uu}		- Saves as a text file.
	@{u}HTML@{uu}		- Saves to a table in HTML.
	@{u}CSV@{uu}		- Saves to CSV file (ViewCSV compatable;)
	@{u}PalmOS@{uu}		- Saves to PalmOS file (Not yet implemented)
@{b}Settings@{ub}
	@{u}Settings@{uu}	- Opens the @{"settings window" link settings}

@endnode

@node requirements
@{jcenter}@{b}Requirements@{ub}
@{jleft}
	ToDoman needs an Amiga (or emulator) running AOS3.x (Possibly 2.x), and a '020.
Probably 4MB FAST ram should do it, might even work under 2 or 1MB chip. Also, it needs
MUI, as well as betterstring, nlist, and Calendar_mcc (that one is probably the least
known, think its on Aminet. Its the one by Alfonso Ranieri). The program itself should
fits on a floppy, and such doesn't require much HDD space. The lists shouldn't either.
Unless your busy as hell... In which case I would recommend a vacation. ;)

@endnode

@node arexx
@{jcenter}@{b}AREXX@{UB}
@{jleft}
	I've added a bunch of AREXX commands, enough you could probably just use a series
of RX "address todo.1;blah blah blah" commands from the shell without touching the mouse.
Except for the annoying requesters that pop up when you do that... Another thing I have
to fix.. Anyway, if you want a list of commands, and don't want to dig up this guide to
get it, you can just use the AREXX tab in the About window. The list on the left shows
the command, the text to the right describes it. In case you're thinking this guide is
going to be more in-depth than that window, its a texteditor object with clip-board
support, which I'm about to use to get the information in the guide, because I'm just
lazy that way. :)

load filename
Loads a new to-do list named filename.

save filname
Saves current to-do list under filename.

export filename format
Saves current list under filename, as a format file.

listinfo item
Returns information about current file, item can be:
    filename
    items
    completed
    outstanding

iteminfo index item
Returns information about index. item can be:
    completed
    entry
    due
    linkto
    notes
    index
    
select index
Selects list entry #index.

entries option
Do the selected option. option can be:
    add
    remove
    purge

complete index
Marks index as complete. index can also be current.

incomplete index
Marks index as incomplete. index can also be current.

modify index item data
Changes index's item to data. Item can be:
    item
    link
    due (mm/dd/yyyy)
    notes

@endnode

@node cli
@{jcenter}@{b}Cli version@{ub}
@{jleft}
	This is the program @{b}witout@{ub} the '-' in it. (MUI version="To-Do", CLI
version = "todo"). This is useful for quickly displaying lists while in a shell. Its
invoked by typing "ToDo @{b}filename@{ub} @{b}options@{ub}". You can have as many
options listed that the shell will allow (I forget what the cap is offhand, but its
not as many as you might think). The lists below should tell you what they do.
	Also, if you use a $deftodo (or whatever) env variable, you can use it as
a filename for this program. I suppose a $defformat or something would work with
the scriptlist output, but I've not tested this yet. My s:shell-startup file has
@{b}todo $deftodo scriptlist all "#v) #d #E[42m#i#E[0m, #s#N"@{ub} in it, so I
get my general to-do list every time I open a shell.

@{jcenter}@{u}Options@{uu}
@{jleft}
help - shows some help text for basic commands.
list @{b}from@{ub} @{b}to@{ub} - Lists the entries within that range.
		@{b}from@{ub} can be @{b}all@{ub} (eg, "todo todo.list list all")
item @{b}Entry@{ub} @{b}item@{ub} - displays a specific item for an entry. Items are:
	@{b}all@{ub}  - Show all the below items
	@{b}note@{ub} - Show the notes for an entry.
	@{b}item@{ub} - Show the entry's name, and if its done or not (eg, "wash socks")
	@{b}date@{ub} - Show the entry's due date
	@{b}link@{ub} - Show the list the entry links to
tofile @{b}filename@{ub} - redirects all output right of it to @{b}filename@{ub}.

scriptlist @{b}from(or all)@{ub} @{b}to@{ub} @{b}format@{ub} - Very useful thing.
		Basically, it formats the output similar to how the lformat option
	in List does. Anything not using an escape code gets printed normally (the
	escape code in this case is a '#' character), while the todo elements can
	be printed with their appropriate codes. The escape codes are as follows:
@{jcenter}@{u}escape codes@{uu}
@{jleft}
	# - Literal '#' character.
	i - Item name (eg, "wash socks")
	l - List item links to (full path)
	d - Items due date (mm/dd/yyyy)
	n - Items note
	v - Index value (item #1,2,etc..)
	s - Items status ("Complete" or "Incomplete")
	N - Newline
	E - Escape (For changing console colors, alarm noises, etc..)

		With these codes, you could almost export a list to CSV or HTML from
	the CLI (though you would need header/footer files to be completely able to
	do this), as long as the "tofile" is able to open the filename. This actually
	is useful enough, I'll probably implement it as an AREXX command in the regular
	MUI version.
		Also, I should note that the commands arguments are parsed left to right,
	and are executed in that order. If you have 2 "tofile" statements, the program
	will close the first file and open the next when it encounters it. This might be
	weird compared to some shell programs, but I find it incredibly useful.
@endnode

